<br>
150 years ago...<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
A cool wind stirred through the Swamp of No Hope. It passed through a land of low lying marshes and bogs, where inhuman creatures had all too human dreams of freedom. The wind dispersed the fog that clung to the water's edge, and blew towards the east. <br>
The cool wind passed through the Field of Bone. It found ancient bones there that brought wonder to the hearts of young adventurers as they passed through. It rattled these bones in its passing.<br>
The cool wind blew through the timeless ruins in the Lake of Ill Omen, and caught up in itself the scent of revolution, and carried this scent with it into the city of the Iksar to the north.<br>
The cool wind blew across the scales of Notuanot, which caused him to raise his face into it and sniff the air. Perhaps, crouching there on the stairs to the Tower of Death, his guildhall, he could smell the dissention the wind had carried up from the south. It matters not to the wind.<br>
Notuanot considered the strange new feel to the air for a moment, then returned his attention to his book. The Truth of Battle, by Rhamukhar. Within its somewhat yellowed pages were the battlefield philosophies of an honored warrior, who's scales had grown soft in his old age, but whose mind was still sharp with the painful, beautiful truths of the ways of war.<br>
Abruptly, Notuanot looked up to the sky and saw the sun entering its first phase, just over the buildings to the east. He stood up and walked into the tower. It was time for his fateful meeting with Arch-Duke Xog.<br>
<br>
..................................<br>
<br>
The Arch-Duke, ruler of the most prominent city in the Iksar Nation, looked down upon the Iksar male kneeling before him on the high parapets of the Tower of Death. There was no emotion in his expression. His scaled lips never parted, and his eyes never left the supplicating figure. &quot;Tell me of your travels to thesouth, Xaxsar.&quot;<br>
Xaxsar lifted his head only slightly, looking at the Arch-Duke's ankles. &quot;My lord, I cannot, nor would not, hide this from you. I lost a valuable tome, to a party of Froglok Raiders. I had on me, at the time, other documents that I would not, for the safety of our realm, part with. I chose to take those documents, and run. The last thing I saw of it, the book was wrestled from a young Squire's hands just before he was slain. The pages were scattered about the swamp.&quot;<br>
The Arch Duke said nothing for a moment. He walked to the parapet wall, and looked down. A Figure had been kneeling there, below them, but he had stood up and walked into the tower. Finally, he turned back to Xaxsar. &quot;You know the price for failure, Xaxsar. Did you think I would be lenient on you, for bringing this to me straightway? Because I know its not in your nature to normally own up to such misdeeds.&quot;<br>
Xaxsar seemed to shrink into himself upon hearing this. He DID know the price for failure, and he was not ready to pay it.<br>
&quot;My Lord, I do only what I must to preserve our realm, surely you-&quot;<br>
The Arch-Duke turned away from him, and grazik knew the conversation was over. He knew death was coming, and he panicked. He stood up and tried to run from his Lord's presence.<br>
The feeling of cold hard steel in his intestines stopped him in mid turn. His eyes bugged out of his head in a fashion that seemed physically impossible. He began to whine, and cry.<br>
Notuanot had seen the figure turn to run as he had followed the Paige's instruction to come to the parapet. Instinctively, he knew that whoever he was, he should not be running.<br>
Rhamukhar taught in his writings, that if you are to do a thing, do it not halfway. Do not timidly place your foot into a place, but tread confidently forward, so that those ahead of you know that you are about business.<br>
Notuanot eviscerated the figure. Staring back at him across the length of his Black Alloy Sword, was the shocked and frightened face of the Arch-Duke's right hand man, his personal agent, Xaxsar. Not once did Notuanot reconsider his actions. Brutally, he shoved the figure back through the red curtain that covered one of the openings onto the parapets.<br>
Xaxsar came to rest at the Arch-Duke's feet. He lay there making whining noises, clutching his opened belly.<br>
Xog looked down at the crumpled Iksar for a moment, then lifted his gaze to meet that of the Shadow Knight whose sword had downed him. &quot;You are the young one I sent for. You are the young Crusader who has shown such promise!&quot; Xog seemed almost happy in saying this. <br>
&quot;Young Crusader, I will not put lightly what I say now. There has just been an opening in my council,&quot; Xaxsar groaned in fright at hearing this said, &quot; and I need someone who has displayed both wisdom and great strength of will. Someone who is well versed in magic, and the ways of war. From what I hear, you fit this description. I may have a use for you.&quot;<br>
Notuanot acted without hesitation. He leaned forward and grasped the cloth insignia draped over Xaxsar's now punctured armor. He wiped the man's blood on it, and resheathed his sword. Then, he knealt before his Arch-Duke.<br>
&quot;I come before you ready to serve, my master.&quot;<br>
The Arch-Duke smiled. &quot;Excellent! Then if you are ready to go to work, prepare to be tested. If you meet my needs, and succeed where I need you to, then I will make you my enforcer. Your name will be written in the pages of history, if you know how to put it there. Right next to mine.&quot;<br>
Xog looked down at Grazik Plaguebringer as he whined for his life and bled it out onto the stone floor. &quot;Notuanot is about to kill you now, Xaxsar. You have dishonored your post, and I have no more use for you. But know this; your pennance for failure shall not end here.&quot; Xaxsar's eyes were nearly out of his skull already, yet the protruded more, and he began to shake all over. &quot;I shall send this young Shadowknight on his first test. It will be to eliminate anything and everything in this city that is remotely related to you. If it was your Clutch-brother, it shall meet you in the the afterlife. If you were mated to it, it shall not wake come the morn.&quot;<br>
Xaxsar was crying now. He pronounced his shame and worthlessness for everyone to hear.<br>
Xog continued. He knealt down, grasping the man by the neck, and lifting him up. &quot;He will go from house to house, from alley to alley, from whores' den to whores' den, to each and every gilly that lifted her tail for you, until nothing that has the blood of your ancestors within its veins breathes. Die like the dog you are!&quot; Xog stood up, gave Notuanot a nod of his head, and walked down the hall.<br>
There was a series of painful cries that echoed through the Royal Quarter. The wind caught these, and gleefully carried them throughout the city, for everyone to hear.<br>
.....................................<br>
<br>
After he had seen his orders through, Notuanot walked back down the hallway, to a study room, where the Arch Duke was waiting for him. He stood just after the entry way, waiting for the Arch Duke to acknowledge him. The Duke sat down in a bone back chair next to a fireplace, and motioned for Notuanot to do the same. He removed his scabbarded sword from his back and leaned it against the wall near him, and sat down.<br>
&quot;The man you just killed lost a very important book in the Swamp of No Hope. It is called the Origins of Pain, and contains great magic. I know it is still out there, as its pages are imbued with magic, and indestructible. Gather the pages from the Froglok Raiders. Find and kill each Froglok that has a page, and bring me his head. Bring me the Origins of Pain. Do this, and I shall set you high in my council. This is your test. Now go.&quot;<br>
Notuanot stood, bowed before the Arch-Duke, and turned to leave, without another word.<br>
The Arch-Duke stopped him before he reached the door, with a single, ominous sentence. &quot;You know the pennance of failure.&quot;<br>
Notuanot turned to meet his gaze, not once blinking or looking away, and uttered several words that would soon cement his role in history. &quot;I AM the pennance of failure.&quot;<br>
He waited for the Arch-Duke's response before turning to leave.<br>
Xog merely smiled at him and said, &quot;We'll see.&quot;<br>
<br>
........................................... <br>
<br>
The Voice of Freedom<br>
<br>
The night air was thick and heavy. A haze of mist tickled at exposed skin. It was not an unpleasant night at all. Indeed, thought Brahm. Good breeding weather. He smiled as he stood at his post on the outskirts of their makeshift village.<br>
Here and there, a contented croak could be heard as his people slept. As they slept free. Not like his brothers, trapped in slavery in the evil Iksar city. However, if they<br>
fought bravely and used all the resources they had, they would have freedom for all their kind.<br>
A twig snapped somewhere nearby. Brahm's great round head swiveled in that direction, the membranes over his eyes made a snapping sound as they opened to full.<br>
Out of the night a tall lean form stepped forward. Moonlight glinted off its scales.<br>
&quot;Who goes there? Know you the sound of freedom?&quot;<br>
&quot;My voice is the sound of freedom,&quot; came the response, in a passable form of the froglok tongue, and the right answer.<br>
&quot;Then come forward, child of freedom.&quot;<br>
The Iksar moved out of the shadows and stopped a couple feet from Brahm. They stood like that for a moment, toe to toe. Then Brahm reached out and embraced the Iksar.<br>
&quot;Glad you made it back, old boy,&quot; Brahm said. &quot;You had us worried!&quot;<br>
The Iksar's eyes were practically glowing with excitement. &quot;We must gather the camp, Brahm, wake them all up! I have news. Most important news!&quot;<br>
&quot;Aye, Rrothmal! We have been waiting for your news. Come, let us tell them all what you've learned.&quot;<br>
Watchman Brahm and Rrothmal the Iksar walked from tent to tent in the camp the Clan Rogpok of the froglok people and the Outcast Iksar shared, until every frog and every iksar were awake, and gathered around a fire in the center of the camp. From close to the center of the camp, a young froglok lass watched Rrothmal with great eagerness as she cradelled a wiggling bundle in her arms.<br>
&quot;My brothers and sister!&quot; Rothmal began. &quot;As you know, myself and a handful of others have been working in secret, as infiltraters within the Iksar nation! And finally, our little alliance may have come upon a way to end our brother's slavery in atleast one city, their capitol City. And strike a blow for freedom, for righteousness and all that is good!<br>
&quot;It was only a week ago that a group of Clan Rogpok's brave warriors did catch a group of the hated Iksar Necromancers travelling through the swamp! Immediately and without hesitation, they attacked! Their zeal earned them a victory, as those vile worshippers of evil that did not die fled before Rogpok's might!&quot; At this, a cheer and much croaking of approval rose throughout the camp.<br>
Once the commotion had settled down, Rrothmal continued.<br>
&quot;And their zeal earned them more than just a meager victory over a handful of Necromancers, for one of those Necromancers was actually the right hand man of Duke Xog, ruler of the Iksar City of Cabilis! And on his person, dropped as he fled from our might, was a tome that we now hold in our possession, one that possesses the secrets to many of their vile spells!&quot;<br>
A froglok Shin shaman named Gormon stepped forward with a book in his hands. He lifted it high into the air, its crimson seal reflecting the moonlight eerily.<br>
&quot;Behold,&quot; declared Rrothmal. &quot;The Principals of Pain!&quot;<br>
A deep hush fell over the assembly. &quot;With this in our possession, thanks to the studious efforts of Gormon and his Shin Brothers, we will now be able to counteract their magicks effectively.<br>
&quot;For now, I must tell you of news, both grave and fortuitous. The acquisition of their cursed tome has not gone unnoticed. Lord Xog is preparing to send into the swamp for it, and he knows where to find us.&quot;<br>
The crowd gasped in unison. &quot;We should flee! Organize now! Pull up all our belongings and move on, as we have done before! Disappear into the swamp!&quot; Roars of approval came from the crowd as they began to feel the tugs of panic on their hearts. They began to mill about, as if to flee.<br>
&quot;No!&quot; shouted Rrothmal. &quot;I refuse to run! I refuse to hide any longer! We have the key to their magicks! We can face them!&quot;<br>
&quot;No, we cannot!&quot; One of the Frogloks shouted. He stepped forward to speak. &quot;We all know the might of their armies. We are few! If we stand our ground, we will be crushed. We must continue to run and hide, to build the revolution!&quot; Murmurs of agreeance.<br>
&quot;Before you turn and flee, hear what I have to say,&quot; Rrothmal said. The crowd settled down for a moment, caught by curiosity at his words. &quot;For Lord Xog is not sending an army, he is not even sending a troop of Shadowscale! He is sending one man!&quot;<br>
The crowd scoffed and chattered among themselves. The one that had spoken up before again stepped forward. &quot;How is this so? They will send one hunter out before us? Surely, no matter how powerful this man is, our Shin Shamans and our<br>
Iksar Manslayers shall be enough to overcome him!&quot;<br>
Rrothmal surveyed the crowd, hoping to himself that his next words would have the desired effect. &quot;They are sending a champion of the Shadows, a creature Duke Xog has been training personally, an enforcer and a dread terminator. Think of this!<br>
&quot;If we could slay this man, this monster, and mount his head in the center of our camp for all to see, then the other Clans would gather about and know that it IS possible for freedom to win! They would gather behind us, instead of hiding in the deep muck on their underbellies! They would unite and we would finally stand a chance against this evil!&quot;<br>
The crowd was hushed now, Rrothmal had them in the palm of his hand. &quot;Heed me! The vile purveyor of Shadows they send is named Notuanot, and he is Arch Duke Xog's new enforcer! He is every bit as evil and heartless as Cazic-Thule himself!<br>
&quot;A victory against him would be a victory that could unite the Clans! What do you say, Clan Rogpok? What do you say, Outcasts? Are you with me? Are we going to hide here in the muck and the mire to live out our lives, or are we going to challenge them for our natural right to freedom?!?!&quot;<br>
The crowd roared with him. Outcasts hissed and growled and frogloks croaked and ribbitted their approval. &quot;Long live Clan Rogpok! Long live freedom!&quot; shouted one man. &quot;Down with the worshippers of Cazic-Thule!&quot; shouted another. &quot;Challenge the Scaled God! Let purity prevail!&quot; For a long time, what seemed like ages, the crowd gathered about Rrothmal and cheered. Finally, it began to disperse, and the leaders led Rrothmal into the war tent for a council meeting.<br>
<br>
..........................................<br>
<br>
Late in the night, after the meetings and the planning were finally over,Rrothmal slipped into the tent of a young froglok lass named Ghel. A soft cooing and rattling noise greeted his ears. His daughter lay awake in Ghel's arms, tugging playfully at her mother's eyelid.<br>
Rrothmal carressed his daughter's cheek affectionately. She was the only one of their eggs to hatch. The Shamans had said that it would be impossible for them to have children, that their races were just incompatible. Yet here lay this little miracle. Some of the elders even considered her so. There was talk of an omen, of a prophesy.<br>
Rrothmal awoke his young wife with a kiss. She rolled over and her eyelids pulled back over her huge, dark green eyes. The protective membranes slowly pulled back as she fought the urge to go back to sleep. &quot;Hey.&quot; she said sleepily.<br>
&quot;Hey.&quot; he smiled down at her. <br>
&quot;You did good tonight, my love. You did good.&quot;<br>
He sat next to her and began to remove his leather armor and swordbelt.<br>
Silence for a moment. Finally, she spoke again. &quot;You think we can actually win?&quot;<br>
Rrothmal sat his swordbelt aside and rolled over next to her. &quot;They said we'd never live above water, and we do. We don't swim in the muck with the lowdwellers anymore. We live in huts, and tents.<br>
&quot;They said you couldn't give me a daughter, and you did.&quot; The child cooed softly and held onto his arm. Now that he was here, she was finally drifting off to sleep.<br>
She looked lovingly into his large eyes. &quot;This thing they're sending... its as bad as you say?&quot;<br>
&quot;This Notuanot? His name is from the ancient tongue. I tried to find out what it means, but my sources inside are pretty scared of him. I don't care. I'll meet him just like we've met every challenge. Somehow, we'll overcome.&quot;<br>
The night embraced mother, father, and child. For three hearts so brave, hearts so out of place in this cruel, evil world, sleep finally came.<br>
<br>
..............................................<br>
<br>
A pair of eyes glowed an unnatural red somewhere in the darkness above their tent. The eyes belonged to a creature who did not care about love, or freedom. A creature who's only motivation was that these beings were in his way, and must be swept away like sandcastles before the tide. For nothing must stand in his way.<br>
A pair of eyes glowed malignantly in the dark, as their owner contemplating freedom's end.<br>
<br>
............................................................. <br>
<br>
The Fall of Freedom<br>
<br>
The mist rose up off the ground and hung in the air, as if waiting for something. It curled lethargically about Brahm's webbed feet as he stood guard. He leaned casually against a tree and tried to stay awake.<br>
Somewhere in the night, a sound was made, a sound that was out of place.<br>
Brahm sturred from his position leaning against the tree. He stretched, emitted a contented ribbit, and stepped out a few feet to listen for what he had heard.<br>
Movement, through the trees. There was the sound of twigs snapping and the gentle noise of moss squishing under foot.<br>
Brahm searched the treeline ahead of him. There. Moving through the trees, a figure. Not at all trying to conceal itself.<br>
Brahm's mind went on alert. As the figure drew closer, he tried to remember if any of their operatives were due back. Did they have anyone that was supposed to be outside of the camp?<br>
The figure parted from the trees now. It was undoubtedly an Iksar. It began to approach him. Not now, not with him on duty! Could this be the one they sent?<br>
&quot;Know you the voice of freedom?&quot; Brahm asked as the Iksar was several paces away. Brahm had his hand on his sabre hilt, in case the Iksar gave the wrong answer. And he did.<br>
&quot;My voice is the sound of freedom dying,&quot; said Notuanot as he drew his blade.<br>
Brahm's last thoughts were panic and fear. His sabre had not even cleared its sheath before his chest was split open. A gusher of blood glistened green in the moonlight as he fell to the ground in a heap.<br>
And so it began.<br>
<br>
..........................................<br>
<br>
A see of panic surrounded him. Froglok warriors and outcast Iksar charged at him and were cut down as they came, with a slash of his sword or a few words of magic. Translucent green skulls flew in every direction from him. They cackled madly and where their voices were heard, all ran in terror.<br>
The shadows themselves came alive and wrestled with those that ran. The night was his to command.<br>
Notuanot became aware of casting that was not his own.<br>
Several of the Froglok Shin Shamans had gathered and were beginning to cast spells.<br>
Another Froglok cried out in terror as he stomped on its head and crushed its skull. Then the flames begin to slam into him.<br>
He braced his shield against the flamestrikes. The heat from the blasts rolled around him in waves. He pushed forward towards the shamans, with his shield held in front of him.<br>
From the other side of the shamans, a pile of bones lept up from the ground and charged towards them. The skeleton dragged one shaman to the ground and he croaked in agony as he was impaled upon its ribcage. <br>
The other Shamans had their attention divided for an instant.<br>
That was long enough. Notuanot was among them, blade slashing open stomachs and removing limbs. Their knowledge of his magics was not saving them now. They had only learned enough to understand how he was killing them.<br>
The shadows continued to smother and grab at his foes. The skulls continued with their eerie laughter that turned brave men into cowards. The revolution continued to fall.<br>
<br>
...................................<br>
<br>
&quot;He is a monster! Take the book and run, damn you! We will all die!&quot; The Shin Shaman told his Elder, Foraak, who knealt in the tent with the Principals of Pain open in front of him, desperately trying to glean some last minute miracle from its pages.<br>
&quot;I will not run. Rrothmal was right. We have run for too long.&quot;<br>
Foraak turned the pages desperately, searching for one last rune. He was onto something.<br>
&quot;Rrothmal will die too! Death is upon us!&quot; The Shin fled from the tent to join the rest in their madcap scamper. Foraak no longer saw him. His mind was beginning to tie together several runes from the Prinples of Pain. He could see them forming, understand what they meant. They meant death to Notuanot.<br>
<br>
.....................................<br>
<br>
All about him were bodies. Where he found one still twitching, he would stick his blade into it until it stopped. He searched through the tents and finished any he found there.<br>
A Froglok Shin Shaman darted blindly through the foggy camp.<br>
He ran right into Notuanot's shield. He bounced off and collapsed. Notuanot removed his head before he even realized he had been knocked down. <br>
Notuanot made his way through the tents. From one, he heard the unmistakeable chanting of magic. He also recognized the runes being called forth as some of the runes used in his own magic. He tore the tent flap away and stepped in.<br>
<br>
................................<br>
<br>
Foraak's eyes turned black and darkness poured out of them.<br>
He tried to open his mouth and scream, but darkness poured from his mouth, and when he tried to breath, it was snorted from his nostrils.<br>
