...He stumbled back and forth as if drunk. His new legs did not want to support him. He fell face down into the dirt. He heard the footsteps. Giants. Two of them by the sound.<br>
...He rolled over and looked up. Their huge bodies obscured the night sky. One's visage was framed by the moon. Its voice shook the ground. &quot;Little lizard man. We feed on you, little lizard man. You good food!&quot;<br>
...Brainless. Useless. Giant sacks of execrement! Suddenly his legs would work. He stood up and looked high into the night to meet the giant's gaze. &quot;In my darkest hour,&quot; he said &quot;did my greatest strength show. As I lay in my tomb, did my soul quicken to the dark lord.&quot;<br>
...&quot;Lets play... kick the lizard!&quot; One of the giants booted him across the Dreadlands. He was knocked through a tree. He heard it snap in two under his weight and momentum, yet he felt...nothing. He stood back up, his back broken, and still felt nothing.<br>
...&quot;Kick the lizard!&quot; bellowed the other giant with utter unabashed glee. It charged across the distance and drew back its foot with almost poetic grace. Notuanot shadowstepped.<br>
...The giant's foot cut through the shimmering remains of Notuanot's magic. He was on the other side of it now, and had already begun to cast a spell.<br>
...&quot;Oh, golllllly!&quot; exclaimed the first giant. It stumbled backward in stark terror and fell on its ass.<br>
...&quot;What be wrong with you?&quot; asked the second giant. Notuanot unleashed the shadows. They simmered up from the ground and crawled up the second giant's legs as the first one ran in the opposite direction uprooting the sycamore and oak trees of the dreadlands in its wake.<br>
...The remaining giant struggled against the shadows and reached forward and down toward Notuanot. &quot;Gonnnna get yooou!&quot; it howled. The wind picked up the noise and carried the eerie howl throughout the land.<br>
...&quot;Never!!!!&quot; Notuanot raged into the night air. The Harmtouch he had been taught by Xog himself so long ago manifested tenfold, empowered by the god of death.<br>
The Harm exploded in the giant's chest cavity and blew its upper torso into a thousand bloody pieces. As they rained down on him, Notuanot felt... nothing.<br>
...The Giant's lower body and legs just stood there for a moment, dazed. Then, slowly, it too toppled. Notuanot let it fall toward him. He did not care. He felt nothing. Numb inside. A peaceful numbness.<br>
...Then the impossible happened. As the remains of the giant toppled forward, surely to crush him, Notuanot unleashed a second Harmtouch. It blew the giant to pieces as it fell forward and its remains fell about Notuanot like blood rain.<br>
...He stood there for a long time, drenched in gore. It had begun to snow. The cold bitter wind bit at his scales, but he felt it not. The cold bitter wind sang its lonely song to him, and it comforted him somehow.<br>
...Notuanot, who had just this evening found his new legs, began to run. He ran through the mountains and into a cave. Through the cave spread a vast wasteland sparsely populated by only a few trees. He kept running. He ran past the ruins of a castle that had been built and had collapsed in the time he had been entombed. He ran through snow covered hills.<br>
...His leg muscles tore and bled from within, but he felt nothing. They regenerated as fast as they could tear and he kept running.<br>
...His undead lungs lay dormant in his chest. A pair of useless reminders of what he once was. He did not need them to drive him now. He felt nothing. He ran.<br>
...He tripped over a cliff and fell, bouncing down the side of a mountain. He came to rest with a grunt against something solid and white. He looked up into the eyes of a great white dragon. &quot;Here now, child. Why be you running so? You've been running around here for weeks! You must be tired.&quot;<br>
...Notuanot sprang to his feet and growled at the dragon. &quot;You stupid fat cow! Dont you see!? I feel NOTHING! It hurts no more! It hurts no more!&quot;<br>
...The dragon snorted a halfhearted ring of smoke into the air. &quot;I'm not fat,&quot; she said, and batted her giant eyes shut. The sound was like stone grating on stone. She shifted her weight and huffed, and a landslide started nearby.<br>
...Notuanot took off up the side of the cliff. The dragon called after him, &quot;You ought to sit down for awhile!&quot;<br>
...Notuanot ran. He reveled in the painlessness. Pain is a reaction your nerves have to tell you that you are damaging yourself, or being damaged. The nerves in Notuanot's body were all dead. HE was dead. All his life the sensations that had weighed him down, they were all gone now.<br>
...He felt no fear. For the first time in his existence, he felt no obligation to fear anything. Not Thule. Not death. He had overcome death. Or rather, death had overcome him.<br>
...Notuanot ran. He came to a land afire. He found a giant wasp with a fiery stinger that tried to sting him. He let it.<br>
It's giant fiery stinger pierced his scales. It was the most glorious sensation he had ever felt. There, just barely, underneath the scales, was the ghost of pain. Well buried underneath callouses and decayed scales that were slowly turning to stone.<br>
...Notuanot let the giant wasp sting him again and again. Eventually, the wasp collapsed to the ground. It had torn its stinger and had bled to death. <br>
...Notuanot ripped the stinger from its corpse and plunged it into his belly. The flames tore him apart from within. He pulled the stinger out and watched the scales reknit themselves over the wound. The wound healed itself from within. <br>
...Again, and again, and again, Notuanot jabbed the stinger into his own body, until the fire died upon its tip and it was nothing more than a hardened piece of cartilage. Notuanot tossed it aside and rolled over on his back.<br>
...He looked up at the stars. He looked up at Luclin. He lay there. Not panting. Not exhausted. Just there. his wounds had healed, and always would. His body required no sustenence now to fight off fatigue, no rest, no sleep. All it required was...<br>
...Blood. He would need to feed soon. The fat white dragon had said he had been running for weeks. If so then, how long had he been running now? He felt the hunger burning within him. It was the first sensation he could actually fully feel.<br>
...He panted and writhed on the charred ground. He howled into the night. The sound was the only sound to be heard for miles and miles. Notuanot lurched to his feet.<br>
...&quot;Someone... is going to die now.&quot; He looked up and saw the sun burning overhead. He had not noticed it. It mattered not. He could not feel the sun on him. He could not feel anything but the hunger. He let it consume him and followed it where it led him. <br>
...It led him to Firiona Vie, and to the blood of high elves. There, drenched in their blood, he could feel again. He could feel the hunger ebb and subside as he gorged. He could feel it rise and flow through him. <br>
... He would play games with it. He would starve himself from blood until it hurt so bad he could not move. He would lay where he was and shiver. He would lay this way until something to feed upon ventured close enough. By this time he was in a frenzy and let the frenzy control him. Then, at last, he would feed.<br>
...He would go into towns at night and kill, merely to see the blood flow. He would gorge himself until he could drink no more. Then he would spill the blood purely for sport. <br>
...Ages came and went. Decades passed. They came to know his name. They came to fear him. He did not care for their fear. Only for their blood and their death.<br>
...They sent out a party of vampire hunters, believing that one of Mayong's berserk creatures had somehow found its way into the wilds of Firiona Vie. As their population dwindled, they searched in vain. <br>
...Finally, they caught him. So gorged was he that he lay in a state of torpor, unable to move, unable to care. Perhaps it was more a state of curiosity to see what they would do. What they COULD do to him. Would they be able to make him feel?<br>
...They could not find a way to kill him. His flesh was like stone, unable to be pierced or sliced. Poison and flame washed over him with no effect. At times he howled in laughter at them.<br>
...With nothing else to do, they decided to take him out to sea and toss him into the water in a great sarcophogus. The boat never returned to shore. In fact, years later, a boat drifted and ran aground just south of Freeport near the shores of the Desert of Ro. There were no passengers or crew upon that boat. Only a single sarcophogus sitting on the deck, covered in chains and broken magical runes...<br>
